Hi,
I’ve pulled together the initial estimate of the potential uplift from a simple 2-hop network approach using 2024 confirmed bads.
Methodology:
•	Started from the 2024 population of confirmed bad BUK personal customers (38.6k).
•	I identified 1-hop connections using shared attributes (phone / address)
•	From those 1-hop nodes, I then looked at 3rd party transactions over the 12 months prior to the initial case start date (seed detection date).
•	From these transactions, I identified other Barclays customers (2-hop layer) and evaluated which were subsequently confirmed as bad after the case date of the seed node (0-hop / first node in the network).
Key results:
•	4,365 customers were confirmed as bad at a later date and had 2-degree connections to earlier confirmed bad customers
•	Median time between initial bad detection and 2-hop customer detection: 146 days.
•	Total transaction value (1st party transactions were excluded) between initial detection and subsequent 2-hop detection: £313m.
•	Of this, £12m relates to cash withdrawals, £13m to cash deposits, £155m to credits and £159m to debits.
 
